T1  - MEDIEVAL MATCHING MARKETS
AU  - Boerner, Lars
AU  - Quint, Daniel
Y1  - 2023/02/01
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12600
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 23
EP  - 56
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12600
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We study the regulation of brokerage in wholesale markets in premodern Central Western Europe. Examining 1,804 sets of rules from 82 cities, we find brokerage was primarily a centralized matchmaking mechanism. Brokerage was more common in towns with larger populations, better access to sea ports and trade routes, and greater political autonomy. Brokers' fee structures varied systematically: price-based fees were more common for highly heterogeneous goods, quantity-based fees for more homogeneous goods. We show theoretically that this was broadly consistent with total surplus maximization, and that brokerage was more valuable in markets with unequal numbers of buyers and sellers.
ER  - 

