T1  - THE DISTRIBUTIONAL EFFECTS OF COVID-19 AND OPTIMAL MITIGATION POLICIES
AU  - Hur, Sewon
Y1  - 2023/02/01
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12601
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 261
EP  - 294
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12601
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract This article develops a quantitative heterogeneous agent?life cycle?epidemiological model that is used to study the aggregate and distributional consequences of COVID-19 and mitigation policies. First, a stay-at-home subsidy is preferred to a lockdown because it reduces deaths by more and output by less. Second, Pareto-improving policies can reduce deaths by nearly 45% without any reduction in output relative to no public mitigation. Finally, it is possible to simultaneously improve public health and economic outcomes, suggesting that debates regarding a trade-off between economic and health objectives may be misguided.
ER  - 

